GEMINI-CURSES(1)           User Commands           GEMINI-CURSES(1)

NAME
    gemini-curses - ncurses terminal interface for the Gemini API

SYNOPSIS
    gemini-curses
    gemini-curses <session_name>
    gemini-curses --resume <session_name>
    gemini-curses --list
    gemini-curses --models
    gemini-curses --test-model <model_id>
    gemini-curses --version
    gemini-curses --help

DESCRIPTION
    gemini-curses is a Python ncurses interface for Gemini. It is the
    full-screen terminal interface companion to the Bash gemini-cli tool.

    It provides:
        - scrollable transcript area
        - multiline input box
        - wrapped input display
        - input placeholder text
        - monochrome display mode
        - compact low-resolution-safe command strip
        - clickable command strip labels
        - actionable F1 command menu
        - proper cursor movement
        - mousewheel scrolling
        - mouse-assisted input cursor placement
        - mouse-assisted model selection
        - named and resumable sessions
        - session browsing and session renaming
        - timestamped logs
        - rolling conversation context
        - explicit context snapshots saved in session logs
        - view/edit/clear/rebuild memory tools
        - attachment extraction for code blocks
        - file attachment support for outgoing Gemini requests
        - response inline attachment saving where returned by the API
        - in-app model selection and model testing
        - in-app API key entry with runtime-only default behavior
        - options menu for editable config keys
        - external editor support
        - credits/about screen
        - temporary project-lead startup notice in new blank sessions

USAGE
    First-time setup from inside the interface:

        gemini-curses
            Press F3 to paste an API key.
            Press F2 to list models, highlight one, and press t to test it.
            Activate or save the model after reading the test response.

    First-time setup from the shell:

        gemini-curses --models
        gemini-curses --test-model <model_id>

    Start a normal timestamped chat:

        gemini-curses

    Start a named full-screen chat:

        gemini-curses android-backup

    Resume a named chat:

        gemini-curses --resume android-backup

    List saved chats:

        gemini-curses --list

    Test a model from the shell:

        gemini-curses --test-model gemini-2.5-flash

SESSION MANAGEMENT
    gemini-curses
        Start a new timestamped session.

    gemini-curses <name>
        Start or open a named session.

    gemini-curses --resume <name>
        Resume an existing named session. If the session does not exist,
        the command exits with an error.

    gemini-curses --list
        List saved sessions.

    F4
        Open the session browser. The browser can switch sessions, rename
        highlighted sessions, or rename the current session.

DISPLAY AND LOW-RESOLUTION BEHAVIOR
    The main chat view uses a compact command strip between the transcript
    and the input field. The strip is designed to avoid half-cut labels on
    low-resolution terminals.

    Visible command-strip labels are clickable. Labels that do not fit are
    not drawn; press F1 for the complete command menu.

    F1 opens a full-screen actionable command menu. From the F1 menu, users
    may launch features by pressing their function key, by highlighting a row
    and pressing Enter, or by clicking a row.

    Long help, credits, and error messages are shown as full-screen scrollable
    pages. These pages support PgUp, PgDn, mousewheel scrolling, q, and Esc.

    New blank sessions may show a temporary transcript notice from
    remfan1994. This notice is not written to the session log, is not sent to
    Gemini, and disappears when the first user message is sent.

    The input box displays placeholder text when empty. The placeholder is
    visual only and is not part of the prompt.

    By default, user transcript messages are drawn dim/grey and Gemini output
    is drawn normally. Text being typed in the input box is drawn normally.

    Set MONOCHROME=1 in the config file to avoid dim/grey styling.

MODEL DISCOVERY AND TESTING
    Available Gemini models can be listed from the command line:

        gemini-curses --models

    They can also be listed directly with curl:

        curl "https://generativelanguage.googleapis.com/v1beta/models?key=YOUR_API_KEY"

    Inside the ncurses interface, press F2 to open the model selector.

    Autoscan has been removed. gemini-curses no longer probes each model until
    one works. Instead, the user chooses a model and explicitly tests it.

    From inside the selector:

        t
            Test highlighted model with MODEL_TEST_PROMPT.

        i
            Show model metadata.

        Enter
            Activate highlighted model for the current run.

        s
            Save highlighted model to config.

    From the shell:

        gemini-curses --test-model <model_id>

    The default model-test prompt is:

        Please reply with one short sentence confirming this model is available
        for text generation.

CONTROLS
    F1
        Show the full-screen actionable help / command menu.

        Inside the F1 menu:
            - function keys launch their features
            - Enter launches the highlighted row
            - mouse click launches the clicked row
            - q or Esc returns to the chat

    Enter
        Insert newline in the input box.

    Ctrl+G
        Send the current message.

    F2
        Open model selector and tester.

    F3
        Open API-key input. The pasted key is runtime-only by default. Saving
        to config requires explicit confirmation.

    F4
        Open session browser.

    F5
        Open options menu.

    F6
        Open memory menu.

    F7
        Open file/attachment menu.

    F8
        Open current input in external editor.

    F9
        Show credits/about screen.

    F10
    Ctrl+Q
        Quit the interface.

    PgUp
        Scroll transcript upward.

    PgDn
        Scroll transcript downward.

    Arrow keys
        Move cursor inside the input box or navigate menus.

    Home
    End
        Move cursor to beginning or end of current input line.

    Ctrl+U
        Clear current input.

    Ctrl+L
        Redraw screen.

    Tab
        Insert four spaces.

MOUSE SUPPORT
    Mouse support depends on terminal emulator support for ncurses mouse
    events.

    Main chat view:

        Mouse wheel up/down
            Scroll transcript.

        Left click in input area
            Place the input cursor near the clicked position.

        Left click visible command-strip label
            Launch that command.

    F1 command menu:

        Mouse wheel up/down
            Move through the command list.

        Left click row
            Launch the clicked command.

    Model selector:

        Mouse wheel up/down
            Move through the model list.

        Left click on a model row
            Highlight that model.

        Double click on a model row
            Activate that model.

    Terminal text selection remains the terminal emulator's responsibility.
    Drag selection is not implemented by gemini-curses.

API KEY BEHAVIOR
    API keys may be supplied by environment variable:

        export GEMINI_API_KEY=your_key

    They may also be placed in the config file:

        GEMINI_API_KEY=your_key

    Inside the interface, F3 prompts for an API key. The key is runtime-only by
    default. Saving it to config requires explicit confirmation. The program
    can also forget the runtime key on request.

    Saving the API key stores it in plaintext.

CONFIGURATION
    Configuration file:

        ~/.config/gemini-cli/config

    Supported keys:

        MODEL
            Gemini model identifier.

        CONTEXT_TURNS
            Number of recent user/assistant exchanges sent back to Gemini as
            conversation context. Default: 12

        HISTORY_LIMIT
            Legacy alias for CONTEXT_TURNS.

        GEMINI_API_KEY
            Optional API key. Environment variable takes priority.

        SESSION_DIR
            Directory used for session log storage. Default: ~/.gpt

        ATTACHMENT_DIR
            Directory used for extracted code artifacts and response
            attachments. Default: SESSION_DIR/attachments

        EDITOR
            External editor command used by F8 and memory editing.

        GITHUB_URL
            URL displayed in the credits/about screen.

        MODEL_TEST_PROMPT
            Prompt used when testing a selected model.

        MONOCHROME
            Disable dim/grey styling when set to 1. Default: 0

        INPUT_PLACEHOLDER
            Placeholder text shown in the empty input box.
            Default: Type your chat message here...

        STARTUP_NOTICE
            Show the temporary remfan1994 project-lead notice in blank new
            sessions when set to 1. Default: 1

OPTIONS MENU
    F5 opens the options menu. Editable config-backed values include:

        MODEL
        CONTEXT_TURNS
        SESSION_DIR
        ATTACHMENT_DIR
        EDITOR
        GITHUB_URL
        MODEL_TEST_PROMPT
        MONOCHROME
        INPUT_PLACEHOLDER
        STARTUP_NOTICE

    API-key handling is intentionally kept in F3 because saving secrets should
    be an explicit workflow.

MEMORY MODEL
    gemini-curses keeps a rolling conversation context in memory.

    CONTEXT_TURNS controls how many recent user/assistant exchanges are sent
    back to Gemini with each request.

    The session log remains the permanent archive. The context buffer is the
    recent window sent back to Gemini.

    gemini-curses writes context snapshots into session logs as system
    records. These records allow memory state to be recovered more explicitly
    than by reconstructing only from transcript text.

    F6 opens the memory menu:

        v
            View current memory.

        e
            Edit current memory in external editor.

        c
            Clear current memory.

        r
            Rebuild memory from session log.

EXTERNAL EDITOR
    F8 opens the current input in an external editor.

    Editor selection order:

        1. EDITOR config key
        2. VISUAL environment variable
        3. EDITOR environment variable
        4. vi

    This follows the general style of tools such as mutt, where longer input
    can be composed in the user's preferred editor.

FILE ATTACHMENTS
    F7 opens the file/attachment menu.

    The menu can:
        - attach a file to the next Gemini request
        - list pending files
        - clear pending files
        - browse saved attachment directory

    Text files are sent as text parts. Other files are sent as inline_data
    parts with detected MIME types when they are small enough for inline send.

    Very large files are skipped and noted in the request.

ATTACHMENT SYSTEM
    Markdown fenced code blocks returned by Gemini are extracted from terminal
    display and saved into ATTACHMENT_DIR.

    The original raw Gemini response remains preserved in the session log.

    File names follow this pattern:

        <session>-<type>-NN.<extension>

    Response inline attachments, if returned by the API, are also saved in
    ATTACHMENT_DIR.

FILES
    ~/.config/gemini-cli/config
        Configuration file.

    SESSION_DIR/*.log
        Session log files.

    ATTACHMENT_DIR/
        Extracted code blocks, outgoing artifacts, and received inline files.

